    1ï¸âƒ£ What is Binary Search?

    Binary Search is an efficient search algorithm used to find an element in a sorted array. It works by repeatedly dividing the array into halves and discarding the half where the target cannot be present.
        â€¢ Time Complexity: O(logâ¡n)
        â€¢ Space Complexity: O(1) (Iterative) or O(logâ¡n) (Recursive due to function call stack)



    2ï¸âƒ£ When to Use Binary Search?

        âœ”ï¸ The array must be sorted
        âœ”ï¸ The problem requires efficient searching (faster than O(n) linear search)
        âœ”ï¸ Can be applied to search, range queries, finding bounds, and peaks




    3ï¸âƒ£ Standard Binary Search Algorithm

        public int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
            int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
            
            while (left <= right) {
                int mid = left + (right - left) / 2; // Prevents integer overflow
                
                if (arr[mid] == target) return mid; // Found target
                else if (arr[mid] < target) left = mid + 1; // Search right half
                else right = mid - 1; // Search left half
            }
            
            return -1; // Target not found
        }




    4ï¸âƒ£ Variations of Binary Search

        ğŸ“Œ 4.1 Finding First and Last Occurrence
            If an element appears multiple times, we may need to find:
                â€¢ First occurrence â†’ Move left after finding a match
                â€¢ Last occurrence â†’ Move right after finding a match

                public int firstOccurrence(int[] arr, int target) {
                    int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1, first = -1;
                    while (left <= right) {
                        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
                        if (arr[mid] >= target) {
                            if (arr[mid] == target) first = mid;
                            right = mid - 1; // Move left
                        } else {
                            left = mid + 1;
                        }
                    }
                    return first;
                }
                public int lastOccurrence(int[] arr, int target) {
                    int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1, last = -1;
                    while (left <= right) {
                        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
                        if (arr[mid] <= target) {
                            if (arr[mid] == target) last = mid;
                            left = mid + 1; // Move right
                        } else {
                            right = mid - 1;
                        }
                    }
                    return last;
                }

            ğŸ”¹ Count of occurrences: last - first + 1



        ğŸ“Œ 4.2 Order Agnostic Binary Search
            If we donâ€™t know whether the array is sorted in ascending or descending, we first check the order and then apply binary search.

                public int orderAgnosticBinarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
                    int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
                    boolean isAscending = arr[left] < arr[right];
                    while (left <= right) {
                            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
                            if (arr[mid] == target) return mid;
                    if (isAscending) { // Ascending order
                                if (arr[mid] < target) left = mid + 1;
                                else right = mid - 1;
                            } else { // Descending order
                                if (arr[mid] > target) left = mid + 1;
                                else right = mid - 1;
                            }
                        }
                        return -1;
                }

        ğŸ“Œ 4.3 Finding Floor and Ceil of an Element
            â€¢ Floor: Greatest number â‰¤ target
            â€¢ Ceil: Smallest number â‰¥ target

                public int floor(int[] arr, int target) {
                    int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1, floor = -1;
                    while (left <= right) {
                        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
                        if (arr[mid] <= target) {
                            floor = arr[mid]; // Store potential floor
                            left = mid + 1; // Move right
                        } else {
                            right = mid - 1;
                        }
                    }
                    return floor;
                }
                public int ceil(int[] arr, int target) {
                    int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1, ceil = -1;
                    while (left <= right) {
                        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
                        if (arr[mid] >= target) {
                            ceil = arr[mid]; // Store potential ceil
                            right = mid - 1; // Move left
                        } else {
                            left = mid + 1;
                        }
                    }
                    return ceil;
                }


    5ï¸âƒ£ Special Cases in Binary Search

        ğŸ“Œ 5.1 Rotated Sorted Array

            If an array is rotated, we find the rotation index (smallest element) first.

                public int findRotationIndex(int[] arr) {
                    int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
                    while (left < right) {
                        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
                        if (arr[mid] > arr[right]) left = mid + 1;
                        else right = mid;
                    }
                    return left; // Index of the smallest element
                }

            â€¢ Clockwise rotations = index of min element
            â€¢ Anti-clockwise rotations = (size - min index)



        ğŸ“Œ 5.2 Searching in a Rotated Sorted Array

            public int searchInRotatedSortedArray(int[] arr, int target) {
                int rotationIndex = findRotationIndex(arr);
                int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;
                if (target >= arr[rotationIndex] && target <= arr[right])
                        left = rotationIndex; // Search right half
                    else
                        right = rotationIndex - 1; // Search left half
                while (left <= right) {
                        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
                        if (arr[mid] == target) return mid;
                        else if (arr[mid] < target) left = mid + 1;
                        else right = mid - 1;
                    }
                    return -1;
                }

    6ï¸âƒ£ Circular Arrays and Binary Search

            In a circular array:
                â€¢ Right neighbor: (i + 1) % n
                â€¢ Left neighbor: (i + n - 1) % n
            This prevents index out of bounds errors.


    7ï¸âƒ£ Binary Search in 2D Arrays (Matrix)
        Row-Wise Sorted Matrix

            public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] matrix, int target) {
                int row = 0, col = matrix[0].length - 1;
                
                while (row < matrix.length && col >= 0) {
                    if (matrix[row][col] == target) return true;
                    else if (matrix[row][col] > target) col--; // Move left
                    else row++; // Move down
                }
                return false;
            }



    â€¢ If sorted row-wise & column-wise: Start from top-right corner.
    â€¢ If fully sorted (1D-like matrix): Convert index using mid = (low + high) / 2.

    ğŸ”¹ Conclusion
        ğŸ”¸ Binary Search reduces complexity from O(n) to O(log n)
        ğŸ”¸ Works best on sorted or monotonic functions
        ğŸ”¸ Can be applied to search, range queries, peaks, rotations, and 2D matrices
